<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-074-148 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 278 315</DOCID><JOURNAL>Software Magazine  Sept 1991 v11 n11 p120(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Sentry Publishing Company Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MS-DOS 5. (Microsoft Corp.'s new version of the venerableoperating system)(Microcomputers: Systems/Utilities) (NewProducts) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   MS-DOS 5.0 (Operating system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOperating SystemsEnhancementsMS-DOS.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft Corp., Redmond, Wash., has unveiled MS-DOSa 5, which providesincreased memory for DOS applications and data files, including those runningunder Microsoft Windows.andM;A new shell, online help, a task swapper and an undelete facility are alsoamong the system's new features.andP;  An intelligent, automated installationprocedure upgrades all PCs, even over a network.andP;  For the first time,Microsoft will provide an upgrade via the retail channel; the upgrade productrequires DOS 2.11 or higher already present in order to install.andM;Most of MS-DOS 5 resides in the first 64K of extended memory, providing moreconventional memory for applications.andP;  In addition, users can now load TSRs,device drivers and network drivers into the upper memory blocks.andM;The new shell in Version 5 provides a menu interface, and its visualappearance is consistent with Windows.andM;The product is available for $99.95.andP;  Microsoft License Paks for large-volumepurchases are $79.95 per computer.andO;</TEXT></DOC>